{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2abbott_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280604616/1945103101/0635.xml":{"full_text":"D. C. Mental Hygiene\nChief Seeks Young\nPsychiatric Aides\nBy JULIA EDWARDS.\nIn an office built to house animals\nfor medical tests. Dr. Leopold Wex\nberg^ a man who enjoys \u201cdoing the\nimpossible,\u201d started in today as di\nrector of the Bureau of Mental\nHygiene by creating the bureau.\n\u201cI know all the obstacles. The job\nwill take infinite patience,\u201d he said,\nwith the air of a man who has it.\nThe first obstacle is the housing\nproblem\u2014both for his bureau and\nhis family.\nThere still are no administrative\noffices available for the bureau, a\nfact that caused Dr. John P. Owen\nto resign ffom the position in June.\nThe Veterans\u2019 Administration will\nretain the space intended for it until\nnext July.\nMeanwhile, the psychiatrist is\nusing a room in the Municipal Cen\nter designed with special walls and\na floor drain so it could be cleaned\nout with a hose.\nTo Conduct Alcoholic Clinic.\nWhen he wants to talk to a\npatient alone, he will have to ask his\nsecretary to stand in the hall. He\nwon\u2019t have to worry about where to\nput the psychiatric social worker\nuntil he finds one.\nBut Dr. Wexberg has found large\nnew quarters for the alcoholic clinic.\nHe will conduct his first session to\nmorrow night in the basement of the\nForce School, 1740 Massachusetts\navenue N.W. Another clinic will be\nopened in the Pope School, Seventh\nand P streets N.W.\nAlthough he has not found an\napartment for his wife and daugh\nter, 7, Dr. Wexberg took two hours\nyesterday to inspect the premises\nand make suggestions. Shocked to\nhear that no physical examinations\nhave been given at the clinic, he\npromptly ordered the equipment for\nthem.\nEducational Plans Included.\nNow he is looking for psychiatrists\nto assist him on a part-time or a\nvolunteer basis.\n\u201cI want young men,\u201d he said,\n\u201cpsychiatrists who are interested in\neducation. We have to give them\nsomething besides patients.\u201d\nDr. Wexberg, who taught psychia\ntry in his native Austria and at\nLouisiana University Medical School,\nintends to make the clinic a school\nof psychiatry and to conduct weekly\nstaff meetings for doctors and\nnurses.\nHe hopes to find a psychologist to\ngive mental and personality exami\nnations. When he gets the alcoholic\nclinics functioning, he intends to\nopen a mental hygiene clinic for\nchildren. He would not attempt\nthat, however, without both a psy\nchologist and a psychiatric social\nworker.\nvi xi__ui_ _ a i __ _\nAX IX1C UUltliiO Vi ViiUUi Vii nv*v\nsolved, he believes that alcoholism\nwould in the long run be reduced\nsince he says, it is the result of\nemotional instability.\nBut there will be a major post\nwar alcoholic problem here because\nthe armed forces did little to treat\nit during the war. Dr. Wexberg as\nserted. The psychiatrist spoke or\nthe basis of three years as a majoi\nin the Army Medical Corps.\nThe Army discharged alcoholic!\nbecause it could not rehabilitat!\nthem in time to send them back\ninto action, he explained. M06t oi\nthe alcoholics he found among sot\ndlers had some prewar history o;\nalcoholism.\nTwo Restaurants Fined\nIn Health Law Violation:\nChilds Co., Inc., was fined $50 yes'\nterday in Municipal Court on i\ncharge that drinking utensils in th<\nrestaurant at 1340 New York avenu<\nN.W. were not thoroughly cleansec\nand sterilized.\nGeorge Tashheuras, described a:\nproprietor of a restaurant at 2110M\nG street N.W., was fined $35 on i\ncharge of permitting the premise:\nto be \u201cunnecessarily unclean ant\nunwholesome.\u201d\nBOSTON.\u2014GERMAN ADMIRAL ARRIVES\u2014Carrying his own luggage, a German admiral (right)\ndisembarks from the troopship India Victory, which arrived yesterday. He is Vice Admiral Eb\nerhardt Godt, reported to be a submarine expert, brought to this country for questioning by\nNavy officials. Man directly behind Godt is Capt. Church of the Provost Marshal\u2019s office.\n\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nBerlin Yanks Send Home Cash\nAt Rate of $250,000 a Day\n07 LUC ABBUUttirU fJCSB,\nBERLIN, Oct. 31.\u2014American sol\ndiers in Berlin arq sending cash\nhome at the rate of about $250,000\na day in a rush to beat impending\nrestrictions on money transfers, ex\npected about November 10.\nDozens of them sleep in front of\nArmy Post Office money order win\ndows in order to be first in line in\nthe morning.\nEach musette bag, cigar box or\npaper sack which the GIs dump on\nthe counter, crammed full of occu\npation marks, adds to the headache\nbuilding up for American military\nauthorities.\nMost of the occupation marks\noriginate on a Russian printing\npress. And in Berlin's black markets,\nI the Russians\u2014and Germans\u2014are\npaying fantastic prices for American\ncigarettes, soap and chocolate bars.\nAll 1UU1 puwcis pi ill U UWJUpttUUIl\nmarks, but the last official report\nshowed the Russians were printing\nmore than the other three combined.\n\u201cNinety-nine per. cent of what\ncomes through our windows is Rus\nsian currency,\u201d said the chief clerk\nat the group control finance office.\n\u201cWhy lots of us even get paid in\nRussian money.\u201d\nA good portion of the amount sent\nhome actually is accumulated GI\npay. Up to September soldiers were\npermitted to send home only 10 per\ncent more than their pay and al\nlowances. The ruling was relaxed\nbecause it worked a hardship on the\nthrifty.\nThe War Department let Amer\nican commanders in Berlin know\nthis week that it lacked appropria\ntions to pay off occupation marks in\nexcess of amounts authorized as\nsoldiers\u2019 pay and allowances.\nMiner's Wife on Trial\nIn Slaying of Husband\nI By the Associated Press.\nWINFIELD, W. Va., Oct. 31.\u2014In a\ncrowded country courtroom Mrs.\nElizabeth Amos, 34, yesterday plead\ned innocent and went on trial ac\ncused of the slaying of her miner\nhusband, whose body was found in\na crude hillside grave.\nThe attractive brown-haired worn*\nan, who kept the secret of Amos\u2019\ndeath for 20 days, contended she\nshot in self-defense when her 200\npound husband attacked her with a\nblackjack.\nTruman\n(Continued From First Page.)\nhad been subjected to \"damaging\ndelay\u201d in the House Committee on\nExpenditures in the Executive De\n1 partments and criticized the House\nand Senate because of the drive to\ni return the United States employ\nment service to State control, de\nspite his insistence that it remain\nfor the present under the Federal\nl Government.\nThe wage-price policy outlined by\nthe President follows closely that\nlaid down in his order of August 18,\ngenerally prohibiting wage increases\ncasing for compensating price\nboosts.\nThat order, however, permitted\nprice increases to offset higher wages\nwhen granted \u201cto correct a malad\njustment or inequity which would\ninterfere with the effective transi\ntion to a peacetime economy.\" An\namending order issued last night by\nthe President spelled out three con\nditions where the OPA could grant\nprice increases to cover wages.\nThese are:\n1. Where the percentage increase\nin average straight time hourly\nearnings since January, 1941, has\nnot equaled the percentage increase\nin the cost of living (estimated at\n30 per cent) between January, 1941,\nand September, 1945.\n2. Increases needed to correct\nwage inequities among plants in the\nsame industry or locality, with due\nregard to normal competitive rela\ntionships.\n3. Increases which the stabiliza\ntion director rules are necessary to\ninsure full production in an In\ndUBtry \"which is essential to recon-;\nversion \"and in which wage rates j\nare Inadequate to attract needed\nmanpower.\nConcession for Employers.\nIn an accompanying question-;\nand-answer statement on wages and!\nprices, Stabilization Administrator;\nJohn C. Collett said any price in-\u2019\ncreases allowed would not neces\nsarily reflect the full amount of the\npay raise -which it offset.\nMr. Truman said that not many\nprice increases would be required to\nmeet this situation. He also speci\nfied that where higher wages are\ngranted without a compensating\nprice increase, the employer may\ncome in and ask for a higher ceiling\nif a six-month trial period shows\nthis is necessary.\nGovernment economists say the\nnumber of workers who would bene\nfit from adjustment of earnings to\nliving costs is difficult to estimate.\nThe Bureau of Labor Statistics in\nestimating that living costs have\ngone up 30 per cent since January\n1941, figured also that average\nstraight time hourly earnings ad\nvanced 4P per cent.\nIn defending the claims of work\ners to higher wages, the President\nsaid millions are suffering a cut of\nmore than 25 per cent because of\nthree factors: Reduction of the\nwork week from 48 to 40 hours, down\ngrading of jobs and transfer from\nhigher paid war jobs to lower paid\npeacetime occupations.\nUnless something is done in this\nsituation, he continued, every line\nof business will feel the reduced s\npurchasing power and widespread\nunemployment will result.\n\"That is what is known as de-\nflation, and It is just as dangerous\nas inflation,\" the President warned.\nMr. Truman conceded that take\nhome pay could not continue as high\nas in wartime. \u201cThere will have to\nbe a drop,\u201d he said, \"but the Nation\ncannot afford to have that drop too\ndrastic.\u201d\nSome people, he continued, have\nurged that both prices and wages\nbe raised, but \"this proposal cannot\nbe accepted under any circum\nstances. To acoept it would mean\none thing\u2014inflation. And that in\nvites disaster.\u201d\nArguing that \u201cthere is room in the\nprice structure for business as a\nwhole\u201d to raise pay, Mr. Truman\nexpressed the opinion that \"most\nbusinessmen would agree that wage\nIncreases are possible,\" if \u201call of us\u201d\nwould approach the issue ip a rea\nsonable spirit, and try to determine\nhow much a particular concern\ncould allow at a particular time.\nSeveral Seasons Advanced.\nThe President said there were sev\neral reasons he believed his wage\nplan feasible.\n1. Elimination of time and one\nhalf for overtime has reduced labor\ncosts per hour.\n2. Surplus of labor is causing the\ndowngrading of jobs.\n3. Increased productivity of labor.\n4. Business is in a favorable post\n5. Excess profits tax is being\nwiped out.\nThe President conceded, however,\nthat \"there are Important limits on\nthe capacity of industry to raise\nwages without getting price in\ncreases,\u201d and that for many con?\ncerns, particularly \u201csmall business,\"\nthe transition period will bring\nmany problems.\nUrges Reasonable Demands.\n\u201cLabor must recognize these dif\nferences and not demand more than\nan industry or company can pay\nunder existing prices and condi\ntions,\u201d he said. \u201cIt has a stern\nrespbnsibility to see that demands\nfor wage increases are reasonable.\u201d\nWith reference to the strike sit\nuation the President said many peo\nple wanted the Government to set\nup a wage yardstick and that he\nhad been criticized \u201cbecause I have\nnot stepped in to lay down the\nlaw to business and labor.;,\u2019 He said\nthat labor troubles \u201cstand in the\nway\u201d of reconversion.\nThis nonintervention was \"delib\nerate,\" he said, because he be\nlieves Government economic controls\nshould be abandoned as quickly as\npossible.\nThe President spoke of his hopes\nTor \u201cachieving industrial harmony\nmd a new approach to human re\nlationships in industry\u201d at the forth\ncoming labor-management confer\nence, and urged labor and manage\nment to get together on their prob\nlems until machinery can be set\nup to maintain industrial peace.\n\"Public opinion will not counte\nnance refusal on the part of either\nmanagement or labor to proceed in\nJ peaceful, free and democratic\nmanner to arrive at just eonclu\nons,\u201d he aald.\nWhile there had been auggeatlons\nlat the War Labor Board would be\nreplaced by a new agency for han\ndling labor wage cases, as a step\nIn the administration's program, the\nPresident said that wartime ma\nchinery would remain unchanged\nfor the present.\nSHEET MUSIC\nMUSIC BOOKS\nFE l\u201c?R\n7T1-, _j\nNose Red Raw\nto a cold?\nT\u00ab rotinvn onartinj irritation and\nMp nation koal, tmooth on a bit of\nwft, toothing, snntiy-mndicatnd\nRESINOL\ns.\n\u00ab4 NEHSV\n(A (AMl jfWKr PARIS jtff...\nIF your neckline is a front-line for multi-strands of pearls\nIF your head is piled high with hat... fur or felt or frou-frou\nIF your face is luminous with *BALP... news-making shade\nin Coty Face Powder\nWarm, lively tint* are spun into \u2018BALr so thoroughly that\nevery particle of the powder is luminous through and through.\nPowder, color, costly perfume all are spun, whirled,\ncydoned into a glowing new experience for you!\nFour glorious fragrances: L\u2019Origan, L\u2018 Aim ant, Emeraude, \u201cParis?\nTo complete the picture: \u2018Bali* Lipstick, \u2018Bali' Rouge.\nCompounded and Copyrighted by Coty, Inc. in the V.S.A.\nM.\nelour-finish Venetian covert of\nrich character, hand-tailored in a\nmanner befitting this luxury fabric\nEnglish huntsmen, devoted to the\nrough sport of coursing game on\nfoot, found that the stubborn un\ndergrowth played hob with the\ncloth of their hunting jackets.\nThey took their problem to the\nweavers, who developed Covert\nCloth tightly woven, very\nstrong, slip-surfaced, the blended\ncolor of heather. Our covert coats\nmask their rugged character under\na handsome velour-finish surface.\nThey are tailored by hand, with\nhand-stitched edges. Authentic\nfield shades.\nOPEN THURSDAYS. NOON TO NINE\nQuality in the 'nth degree\nCROMBIE\nTOPCOATS\nWe\u2019ve taken Camel\u2019s Hair and Lamb\u2019s Wool from\nPersia for \u2018warmth-without-weight\u2019. added the\ncraftsmanship of the famous Crombie Mills in\nAberdeen Scotland for unexcelled looming and\nbrought the finished fabric to this country for de\nsigning and tailoring by America\u2019s finest bench\ntailors to develope the finished product: A TOP\nCOAT THAT IS TRULY QUALITY IN THE \u2019NTH\nDEGREE! Hand stitching and hand\ndetails for extra richness give a perfect\nfinish to a perfect garment_\nOTHER TOPCOATS $35.00 TO $110.00\nRemovable\nSpike Golf Shoes...\nYou will recognize careful, pain\ntaking craftsmanship in these\nsturdy shoes. Plain toe blucher\nwith oil treated soles, storm welt,\nremovable spikes. Sizes 6*4 to 12,\nB to D. Quality and y Qr\nComfort_ iti\nOther Stetson Shoes J0J5 to JiSO\nmmn\nby Sandy MacDonald\nQuality shirting, this Sakana\nrayon broadcloth! Keeps its\ncrisp tone and fine drape\nthroughout innumerable tub\nbings. You\u2019ll like the color,\ntoo; a creamy beige that\u2019s\nperfect with the new o qc\ntie tones-*?\u2022\nGrosner of 1325 F St.\nTomorrow\u2014Our Last Thursday Opening Until 9 P.M.\u2014Effective\nNov. 2nd, Store Hours, 9 to 6 Every Day, Including Thursdays.","height":"31608","width":"22520"}}
